22:12.226 --> 22:21.380
Jesus died to deliver us from sin and sickness, but many Christians have been taught that, for example, Paul had some kind of malady that impaired his vision.

22:22.081 --> 22:23.704
But that's not what the Bible teaches.

22:24.345 --> 22:31.876
When you actually read scripture in context, Paul tells us exactly what his thorn was in 2 Corinthians 12, 7.

22:32.076 --> 22:38.386
He wrote, there was given to me a thorn in the flesh, a messenger of Satan to buffet me.

22:39.074 --> 22:43.401
He literally wrote the Greek word angelos, the same word used for angels.

22:43.962 --> 22:48.509
So this was a demon, a fallen angel that stirred up persecution wherever Paul went.

22:49.390 --> 22:52.595
A thorn in the flesh is a biblical idiom for enemies.

22:53.156 --> 23:01.088
When Paul asked God to remove this demonic harassment, God wanted to keep his servant humble due to the abundance of the revelation he was given him.

23:01.669 --> 23:07.378
So the Lord answered, my grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.

23:08.258 --> 23:17.032
God never promised we would be free from persecution, but He did promise healing, saying that we will lay hands on the sick and the sick shall recover.

23:17.833 --> 23:25.505
Honest Bible scholars say it's very clear that Paul's thorn was not sickness, but persecution goaded by a demonic messenger.

23:26.266 --> 23:32.075
This clarification matters because so many believers have been taught to accept sickness as God's will.

23:33.517 --> 23:36.562
